{{Infobox non-profit | name = Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare (AWCH) | image = AWCHLogo2013.jpg | image_size = 160px | caption = | founder = | type = Hospitalised children [[Charitable organization|Charity]] | tax_id = | founded_date = 1973 | location = AWCH National Office, Gladesville Hospital, Building 40B, Cnr Victoria & Punt Roads, [[Gladesville, New South Wales]] 2111 | coordinates = {{Coord|-33.839285|151.133686|format=dms}} | origins = United Kingdom's [[Peg Belson#Early work|National Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital]] | key_people = | area_served = [[Australia]] | services = Charitable services | focus = [[Children's Rights]] | mission = Charity | method = [[Popular Education]] and [[Activism]] | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | motto = Helping You Help Kids | former name = Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital * Association for the Welfare of Child Health | homepage = {{URL|awch.org.au}} | footnotes = }}
The '''Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare''' is an [[Australian]]-based voluntary organisation that gives non-medical attention and support to hospitalised children and their parents. Formed in 1973, the group changed its name from Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital to Association for the Welfare of Child Health in 1993 and then to Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare in 2007. In 2008, the association co-wrote "Standards for the Care of Children and Adolescents in Health Services," a set of guidelines for treating children and teenagers in wards that are separate from adults. As of 2007, the association was based in [[Gladesville, New South Wales]].
==History== In 1959, the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|United Kingdom's Ministry of Health]] published the [[Platt Report 1959]], a three-year investigative account of the welfare of children in United Kingdom hospital that required hospitals to implement major changes in the non-medical care of children in hospital.<ref name= "celebration">{{Citation |page=423 |work= British Journal of Nursing |publication-date=April 13, 2000 |volume=9 |issue=7 |title=A celebration of 100 years' achievement in child health |author=Ruth Davies | pages= |pmid=11111437 |doi=10.12968/bjon.2000.9.7.6322}}</ref> That led to the 1961 formation of [[Peg Belson#Early work|Mother Care for Children in Hospital]] (MCCH), a group formed to increase the roles mothers had over the care of their child in hospital.<ref name= "celebration"/> By 1965, enough like-minded healthcare professionals joined the mother's group and the group was renamed the National Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital (NAWCH).<ref name= "celebration"/> That led to the formation of similar groups in Canada (Canadian Association for Community Care) and Australia.<ref>{{Citation |page=559 |work= [[Pediatric Nursing (journal)|Pediatric Nursing]] |publication-date=November 1, 2001 |volume=27 |issue=6 |title=Involvement and fragmentation: a study of parental care of hospitalised children in Brazil |vauthors=de Lima RA, Rocha SM, Scochi CG, Callery P | pages= |pmid=12024527}}</ref>
The Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare (AWCH) was founded as Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital (AWCH) on 15 February 1973 in [[Australia]] as a voluntary organisation that gives non-medical attention and support to hospitalised children and their parents.<ref name= "Checkup">{{Citation |work= [[Irish Times]] |publication-date= September 1, 1997|title=Well & Good Checkup |author=Lorna Kernan|accessdate= January 29, 2013 |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/health/1997/0901/97090100027.html}}</ref> The newly formed organisation wanted to make the public aware of conditions for children in NSW's hospitals, including deficiencies in standards of care. The Association was particularly concerned whether parents were allowed to visit freely in hospitals. Years of debate over the need to consider the emotional as well as physical needs of children in hospital lay behind the formation of the new body. The group changed its 1973 name from Association for the Welfare of Children in Hospital to Association for the Welfare of Child Health in 1993, and then to Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare in 2007.
In 2008, the Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare and the [[Royal Australian College of General Practitioners|Royal Australian College of Physicians]] co-wrote "Standards for the Care of Children and Adolescents in Health Services," a set of guidelines for treating children and teenagers in wards that are separate from adults.<ref name= "Call">{{Citation |at=sec. Local, p. 7 |work= [[The Australian]] |publication-date=November 18, 2008 |title=Call for separate wards for children |author=Adam Cresswell |accessdate= January 29, 2013 |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/call-for-separate-wards-for-children/story-e6frg8y6-1111118065230}}</ref> The standard concluded that treating children and teenagers on mixed wards alongside adults exposed the minors to poor care and mental trauma.<ref name= "Call"/> To address this, the Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare proposed in the standard to treat children in separate areas of adult wards where staff are trained in children's needs or in wards that are completely separate from adults.<ref name= "Call"/>
==Publications== * {{Citation|work= Paediatrics & Child Health Division, RACP |publication-date= November 19, 2008|title=Standards for the Care of Children and Adolescents in Health Services |author=Association for the Wellbeing of Children in Healthcare |accessdate= January 29, 2013 |url=http://www.awch.org.au/child-and-adolescent-health-standards.php|display-authors=etal}}
